<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Secretariat of the African Decade of Persons with Disabilities (SADPD) Regional Office, Addis Ababa</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:16pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">DIS 27</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Secretariat of the African Decade of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Persons </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">with Disabilit</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">ies</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> (SADPD) Regional Office, Addis Ababa.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Upon your request for submission of written evidence on</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">how to improve the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">inclusion of disability in the work of the Department for International Development (DFID),</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">SADPD is pleased to submit the following recommendations. SADPD is a continental technical agency that is run and managed by experts with disabilities. It has created a credible niche in the disability programming and policy implementation process by working in partnership with the African Union</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (AU), G</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">overnments, Civil Society and Continental/ Regional and National Disabled People’s Organizations (NDPOs) in Africa. The Secretariat’s vision is an African continent where people with disabilities enjoy their human rights. The three overarching principles underlining the work of SADPD are disability, development and human rights.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We are submitting this recommendation on behalf of SADPD’s regional office in Addis Ababa. The regional office is currently actively working on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Disability Inclusive Peace and Security Project (DIPS) in collaboration with the African Union Peace and Security Department (AU PSD). The DIPS project aims to improve the lives of persons with disabilities in conflict areas of Africa by mainstreaming disability issues in the prevention, management and resolution of conflict in the context of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">AU peace and security framework. We have responded only to those areas </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">where </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> we feel we have somethi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ng to contribute. Thus, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">our recommendation focuses on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">isability i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nclusive peace and security, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">disaster risk management</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, and disability inclusive development.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Key recommendations</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Disability Inclusive Conflict</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> and Disaster </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Management</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Persons with disabilities are often overlooked throughout conflict and the disaster management cycle</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and especially during humanitarian and relief operations; they are seldom considered as important actors in conflict prevention even though they are often more vulnerable during conflicts and displacement.  The UN Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities (CRPD), articles 11 and 32, requires that persons with disabilities benefit from and participate in conflict management, disaster relief, emergency response and D</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">isaster </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">isk </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">eduction (DRR)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> strategies. We strongly feel DFID should seize the moment and lead the way in supporting and implementing disability inclusive conflict management</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">isaster and risk management programmes in Africa.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Conflict and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">isasters are major cause of disability in Africa. Injuries sustained during a disaster or conflict, as well as lack of medical aid, mobility aids and preventative care can lead to a wave of new impairments. We strongly believe DFID should commit itself </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> making its policies and programmes </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> peace</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> security and disaster management disability friendly.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">DFID’s climate resilience programmes, DRR strategies and conflict prevention/mitigation policies should make disability a core, cross-cutting</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, theme. Disability must be included in its</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> post-2015 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> international</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> development framework.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">DFID’s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> international</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> development framework could draw on the Hyogo Framework for Action but should include goals, targets and indicators on disaster risk reduction and resilience that are inclusive of marginalised groups such as persons with disabilities.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Disabili</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ty must be systematically taken </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">up across all aspects of DFID’s disaster and conflict management cycle</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and provision made for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">training personnel in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">disability awareness and inclusion, involving local Disabled People’s Organisations and disability NGOs.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">DFID’s d</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">isaster relief programmes and policies</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and its</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> humanitarian interventions in conflict situations</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> must take into account the need for rehabilitation and follow-up services for persons with disabilities and people injured, in order to prevent and reduce possible disabilities. Community-Based Rehabilitation (CBR)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> should </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">enable </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">consultation and involvement in both planning and intervention. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">All women and children affected by emergencies and conflicts must be ensured protection and access to relief  and reconstruction programmes; this includes women and children with disabilities who might need specific attention and measures during periods of unrest and upheaval.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We  call </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">DFID’s  development framework </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> take into account the knowledge and suggestions of persons with disabilities living in disaster prone countries, in conflict situations and fragile countries, to make sure that goals, indicators and development policies are fully inclusive of the rights of persons with disabilities.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">DFID’s policy and programme development related to disaster and conflict management should draw on the lived experience of disabled people and promote their participation as agents of change</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Disability I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">nclusive Development</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">DFID is seen as one of the most effective development aid provider in the African continent. It has tremendous achievements in supporting developing countries in Africa in their effort for poverty eradication. However, its effort in mainstreaming disability</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> issues</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is not as significant as it should be. Therefore, we call for an inclusive development approach. DFID must build an inclusive vision of development based on the principle that no intervention should be judged successful if it does not include and benefit Persons with disability.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We urge DFID to follow an inclusive development based on a twin track approach. That is:</span></li></ul><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">specific initiatives enhancing the empowerment of people with disabilities, and</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">mainstreaming initiatives which ensure that a disability perspective is included in all development policies and programmes so that they are fully accessible and inclusive</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">DFID should work on bridging the gap between emergency humanitarian aid and long-term development aid which is essential to help people survive conflicts and disasters and get back on the path to self-reliance and dignity. One of th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e lessons DFID must learn</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is that aid must change as needs change.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e st</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rongly urge DFID to work </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">losely with the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Secretariat of the African Decade of persons with</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> disability and other regional </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">DPOs to “Make the Right Real” for Persons with Disabilities in Africa. There have been several regional initiatives for mainstreaming disability in development cooperation in Africa, particularly in the context of regional decades. Such initiatives include the second African Decade of Persons with Disabilities and its accompanying Continen</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">tal Plan of Action (2010-2019).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">DFID should move from quick-impact, top-down programmes to address dire emergencies to longer-term, bottom-up efforts to promote development and institutional reform</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Development programmes need to be based not just on established principles from elsewhere, but also on an assessment at the outset of distinctive conditions at and just above the local level within fragile states. Among these conditions, power dynamics and governance issues proved to be especially important.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Finally, we strongly encourage DFID to support continental o</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rganizations in Africa such as S</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ecretariat of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the African Decade of Persons with Disability and African Union Peace and Security D</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">epartment in their inclusive development programmes aimed at mainstreaming disability issues and persons with disabilities in the prevention, management and resolution of conflicts.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">12 December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>